76561198035557117,Recommended,211740,11499527,"Posted: 31 July, 2014",all,Sleepy Chipmunk,"The original Thief games were some of the first stealthy stealth games, and, in my opinion, the best. It's really hard for me to pick out anything bad to say about this classic, to be honest. And this isn't nostalgia talking, either- I played and finished this game for the first time in the past year. The characters are interesting, looting everything that isn't nailed down and working to get every last scrap of loot and secret adds some nice replayability, the stealth relies on both line of sight, shadows, and sound, and you will probably want to punch the main villain in the face by the end of the game, along with his love of marbel and metal flooring. The only thing that I don't love is how the old graphics make everyone look like a paper mache monstrosity, but I'm pretty sure that there's probably a mod out there to fix that.Seriously, though. This game is wonderful, and it's amazing how cheap it is. Go ahead and give it a try, yeah? If you're a fan of stealth, you won't regret it."
,Recommended,211740,11504303,"Posted: 1 August, 2014",all,M9AX,"'Thief 2' is like 'Doom 2' in the sense that it's the exact same game only better. The core gameplay remains almost entirely unchanged, the engine is identical, and there is only a minor difference in graphics.This game very easy to sell. Did you like the great voice acting, excellent level-desing, outstanding atmosphere, and the innovative, stealth-based gameplay of the first game? Did you hate the levels that featured unkillable zombies and various other creatures? Well, there are hardly any zombies or creatures (you have to go out of your way to find them, and they're very easy to avoid) the voice acting, gameplay, and atmosphere are the same - and the levels are EVEN BIGGER. Thief 3, Thief 4, and Dishonoured can go sit in the corner and cry.One level in Thief 2 has you sneak through an entire town (you can tip-toe on the rooftops, or you can creep through the shadows of the streets) - which culminates in raiding a six-storey high mansion. This is without loading screens, and there are millions of hidden nooks and crannies where you can find various goodies to steal. Another level has you travel through a ruined Aztec city, and another a jungle filled with treehouses. Aside from perhaps 'Deus Ex', this game has the largest and most detailed levels in gaming history (and by 'detailed' I mean rooms with furniture and books you can read, and fireplaces that lead to secret passageways - not 'detailed' in a graphical sense)Whilst I recommend playing 'Thief 1', and even 'Thief 3' (avoid 'Thief 4') if you must only play one Thief game...make it this one."
76561197993283908,Recommended,211740,10996899,"Posted: 1 July, 2014",all,Metal B,"In 1998 Thief 2 stole a position of my personal list of best games ever. And never gave it back! Looking Glass took the revolutionary concept of the the first installation and brought it to perfection. Thief 2 gives you a lot of options, big levels and lets the player freely find his own way to the goal. The game is more about problem solving then it is combat. Who things power fantasy has to be about killing and murdering, never tried to get around one guard without getting seen or even noticed. Be smart, be observant, be quiet and become a master thief.The game of course suffers of its old age. All the objects consist of only a few polygons, there aren't complex lighting and shading systems at work (which is a shame for a game about shadows) and the environment can look empty or sterile at times. But it isn't unplayable either. If you get use to the graphics, Thief 2 shines with a very interesting world of little stories, fantastic level-design and impressive sound-design.Thief 2 is still the stealth-game in gaming-history."
